==Production==

===Development===
[[File:Vishal Bhardwaj.jpg|thumb|left|Bhardwaj added some Bollywood elements and a dark and serious side into the script he brought from a Kenyan writer]]

During a scriptwriting workshop held by [[Mira Nair]] in 2005,<ref name="script">{{cite web|title='Saif too old, Shahid right for Kaminey'|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-07-22/news-interviews/28165651_1_kaminey-shahid-mira-nair|author=Mirani, Indu|work=The Times of India|date=22 July 2009|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref> Cajetan Boy, a Kenyan writer from Nairobi, showed [[Vishal Bhardwaj]] a script about twin brothers from the city's slums and the events that occur in their lives during a 24-hour period.<ref name="script"/><ref name="mm">{{cite web|title=Scripting Kaminey|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/index.aspx?Page=article&sectname=Columnists%20-%20Aseem%20Chhabra&sectid=54&contentid=20090816200908160227317342d851a34|author=Chhabra, Aseem|work=|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=17 August 2013|archiveurl=http://lite.epaper.timesofindia.com/mobile.aspx?article=yes&pageid=25&edlabel=MMIR&mydateHid=16-08-2009&pubname=&edname=&articleid=Ar02500&format=&publabel=MM|archivedate=20 November 2014}}</ref> Bhardwaj liked Boy's approach to the script; Nair and Bhardwaj discussed it and thought it was a typical Bollywood [[Masala (film genre)|masala]] film.<ref name="script"/> Boy sent Bhardwaj another draft of his script. Three years later, Bhardwaj asked Boy to sell him the idea, and he later bought the script for US$4,000.<ref name="script"/> Bhardwaj revisited the idea and added some Bollywood elements and a dark, serious side to the script.<ref name="script"/> He worked on the original idea with writers [[Sabrina Dhawan]], [[Abhishek Chaubey]] and Supratik Sen.<ref name="mm"/><ref name="rediff">{{cite web|title='Kaminey is a reminder that we have a dark side'|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-vishal-on-kaminey/20090812.htm|author=Pais, Arthur J|publisher=Rediff.com|date=12 August 2009|accessdate=4 June 2013}}</ref> He included Dhawan in writing the screenplay because as he thought she would give it a "solid structure".<ref name="rediff"/> Bhardwaj said that during the writing of the screenplay, most of the original ideas were changed and the climax was "Indianized".<ref name="rediff"/> His re-worked version now included one brother with a stammer and the other with a lisp.<ref name="script"/> Bhardwaj said that despite the complicated structure, ''Kaminey'' is "anything but [[art film|arty]]" and could not alienate audiences in any part of India, and that it is a simple story but with a complicated structure.<ref name="rediff"/> Dhawan said that the film's script was complex and has multiple stories which required excessive writing and rewriting to make each character sound distinct.<ref name="mm"/>

The media showed concern over the film's title, deeming it "odd", and some people were shocked because of the title, which can be translated into English as "mean".<ref name="title">{{cite web|title=Kaminey not an abuse, it's an endearment: Gulzar|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Entertainment/Kaminey-not-an-abuse-it-s-an-endearment-Gulzar/Article1-445941.aspx|author=Jha, Subhash K.|work=Hindustan Times|date=22 August 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref><ref name="title2">{{cite web|title='The person behind the camera is the most kamina'|url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/17/slide-show-1-vishal-bharadwaj-on-kaminey.htm?print=true|author=N., Patcy|publisher=Rediff.com|date=17 August 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> However, the makers said that "kaminey" is not a negative term and is actually a term of endearment.<ref name="title"/> According to Bhardwaj, the idea for the title came from a scene from [[Gulzar]]'s ''[[Ijaazat]]'' (1987), in which the lead actor ([[Naseeruddin Shah]]) refers to the actress in a loving manner; it was the first time that he heard the word used that way.<ref name="title2"/> Bhardwaj told [[Rediff]], "when the script of this film was written, it was like discovering your own mean side. The format of the film is of a caper and all the characters in this film, excluding one, has an agenda. So I thought it was an apt title for the film".<ref name="title2"/>

===Casting===
Shahid Kapoor was cast in the film's lead role. Several media outlets reported that Bhardwaj considered many actors before casting Kapoor in the role, which he refused.<ref name="script"/> Bhardwaj refuted the claims, saying, "There is a huge difference between discussing and narrating and offering someone a film and I would like to clear up the rumour by saying that Kaminey was never offered to anyone else and so no one rejected it."<ref name="script"/> Kapoor said that he accepted the role after reading the script. Priyanka Chopra was cast to play Sweety, the lead female role. She initially turned down the role, saying she felt it was a boys' film and her eight-scene part did not seem good enough. However, Bhardwaj persuaded her to accept the role.<ref name="outlook">{{cite web|title=Krzysztof... In Meerut|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/printarticle.aspx?261415|author=Joshi, Namrata|work=Outlook|date=31 August 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> The idea for casting the screenwriter [[Amol Gupte]] came from the casting director Honey Terhan.<ref name="title2" /> Gupte said that when he received a call from Terham, he thought it was a joke. He stated, "A man named Honey introduced himself as Vishal Bhardwaj's casting director and offered me a very important role. I banged the phone down not believing a word of what he said".<ref>{{cite web|title=I thought Kaminey offer was a crank call: Amol|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Entertainment/I-thought-Kaminey-offer-was-a-crank-call-Amol/Article1-446435.aspx|author=Jha, Subhash K.|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 August 2009|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> However, after meeting Bhradwaj and hearing a script reading, he loved the story and accepted the offer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the 'Kamina' in Kaminey|url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/jul/06/slide-show-1-meet-amol-gupte-the-actor-in-kaminey.htm#2|author=N., Patcy|publisher=Rediff.com|date=6 July 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> The actors Chandan Roy Sanyal, Shiv Subramnayam, Hrishikesh Joshi, [[Rajatava Dutta]] and [[Deb Mukherjee]] were cast in supporting roles.<ref name="cast">{{cite web|title=Meet the cast of Kaminey|url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/jul/21/slide-show-1-meet-the-cast-of-kaminey.htm#1|author=N., Patcy|publisher=Rediff.com|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> For the role of drug dealer Tashi, Bhardwaj chose his friend Tenzing Nima{{mdash}}a tour operator in Mussoorie{{mdash}}saying he had the character and attitude he wanted, and a weird sense of humour.<ref name="outlook"/>

===Characters===
[[File:Shahid, Priyanka and Kunal Kohli promote 'Teri Meri Kahaani' at IIFA 2012 01.jpg|thumb|right|Kapoor (''left'') plays two identical twins <U+2014> one has a lisp and the other stutters, while Chopra (''right'') plays a Maharashtrian girl]]

Bhardwaj instructed the film's entire cast and crew to watch caper classics such as ''[[Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels]]'' (1998), ''[[Snatch (film)|Snatch]]'' (2000), ''[[Pulp Fiction]]'' (1994) and ''[[True Romance]]'' (1993) to study the nuances and become familiar with the genre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaminey team studied to get it right!|url=http://www.bollywood.com/kaminey-team-studied-guy-ritchie-and-tarantinos-caper-classics|author=Tuteja, Joginder|publisher=Bollywood.com|date=17 June 2009|accessdate=25 June 2013|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141120071852/http://www.bollywood.com/kaminey-team-studied-guy-ritchie-and-tarantinos-caper-classics|archivedate=20 November 2014}}</ref> Shahid Kapoor played both Charlie and Guddu, twin brothers with speech impediments; Charlie has a lisp and Guddu stammers. The producers did not want them to look like caricatures, so Kapoor prepared for both roles by meeting and interacting with speech therapists and people with these impediments. According to Kapoor, the producers wanted to find out about the medical reasons for the impediments and their mental effects. They met specialists and thoroughly researched stammering and lisping. Kapoor said that each role had its own challenges. Charlie's physique was very different from Kapoor's and it took him nearly a year to change the look of his body. He found changing from one character to the other difficult.<ref name="two">{{cite web|title=Two in one|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090813/jsp/entertainment/story_11353178.jsp|author=Gupta, Pratim D.|work=The Telegraph|date=13 August 2009|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>

Chopra described her character Sweety as "feisty and vivacious".<ref>{{cite web|title=Double-role in 'Kaminey', the best in recent times: Shahid|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/doublerole-in-kaminey-the-best-in-recent-times-shahid/499257/|work=The Indian Express|date=7 August 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> She said, "Sweety is very busy, and does not have time to take care of her looks and apply make up. Her only aim in life is to bunk her lectures and visit her boyfriend's college or stay in his hotel, and eventually marry him." Chopra described both her character and herself as being "outspoken and fun loving" as well as honest and unable to "hide something that is wrong". She said she had a different cultural background to Sweety, and found it challenging to convincingly portray a [[Maharashtra|Maharashtrian]] [[Marathi people|Marathi]] girl.<ref name="character">{{cite web|title='I am the biggest Kamina after Vishal Bhardwaj'|url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/12/slide-show-1-priyanka-in-kaminey.htm#2|author=N., Patcy|publisher=Rediff.com|date=|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> She had to adopt body language and a Maharashtrian accent to suit the character. She learnt the [[Marathi language]] to make the character as authentic as possible, which she found difficult as a [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]]. Chopra said: "I am speaking a lot of Marathi in the film. It was difficult for me because it's a difficult language and I am not good at Marathi. But I think it's my luck that through Kaminey I got to learn one more language."<ref name="language">{{cite web|title=Priyanka takes up a 'reel' challenge|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/content/articles/2009/07/03/bollywood_news_priyanka_feature.shtml|publisher=BBC|date=3 July 2009|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>

Gupte described his character as mercurial, and found playing him a physical delight.<ref name="tele">{{cite web|title='It was like a picnic'|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090811/jsp/entertainment/story_11343785.jsp|author=Gupta, Pratim D.|work=The Telegraph|date=11 August 2009|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> Gupte said his character keeps the frame unpredictable and that it provided him with a foil to express rage and anguish.<ref name="tele"/> He worked a lot on his characterisation and tried to bring in his own references from European and Japanese cinema.<ref name="tele"/> Chandan Roy Sanyal described his character Mikhail as provocative, mad, wicked and humorous.<ref name="cast"/> Subramnayam and Joshi, who played Lobo and Lele respectively, described their characters as the most corrupt policemen in their department at the Anti-Narcotics Bureau. They said that to prepare for the roles they followed the script and Bhardwaj's instructions to get the characters right.<ref name="cast"/> Mukherjee prepared for his role as Mujeeb by reading the script and understanding the characters, and discussing it with Bhardwaj.<ref name="cast"/> Dutta, who played Shumon{{mdash}}a Bengali criminal involved in fixing horse races and arms dealing{{mdash}}said that he did not have much time to prepare for his role because he was given the script after he arrived in Mumbai, where Bhardwaj briefed him.<ref name="cast"/>

=== Filming ===
[[Principal photography]] commenced in mid-2008, and the film was mostly shot in Mumbai.<ref>{{cite web|title=From Omkara to Kaminey|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090416/jsp/entertainment/story_10827148.jsp|author=Gupta, Pratim D.|work=The Telegraph|date=16 April 2009|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> During a late night shoot for a scene in [[Pune]], Chopra received minor injuries. Chopra was supposed to ride a motorcycle with Kapoor seated on the pillion seat. Both fell off the motorcycle as it skidded on mud. Kapoor was unhurt but Chopra received scratch marks and bruises.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shahid-Priyanka's bike mishap|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/1185082/report-shahid-priyankas-bike-mishap|author=Mazumder, Ranjib|work=Daily News and Analysis|date=22 August 2008|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> It was reported that Kapoor suffered from several injuries while shooting.<ref>{{cite web|title=When stars got injured while shooting|url=http://www.mid-day.com/photos/b-town-specials/when-stars-got-injured-while-shooting/shahid-kapoor/|work=[[Mid Day]]|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> During filming, Chopra became hoarse because she had to scream her lines; an essential part of her role as an "extremely vocal Maharashtrian girl."<ref>{{cite web|title=Priyanka loses her voice following Kaminey shoot|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/priyanka-loses-her-voice-following-kaminey-shoot-news-bollywood-kkfsOohaicd.html|author=Indo-Asian News Swrvice|publisher=Sify|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Some important railway sequences were shot at Wadi Bunder Yard near Sandhurst Road.<ref>{{cite web|title=CR basks in Kaminey glory, eyes some more|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/cr-basks-in-kaminey-glory-eyes-some-more/509750/|author=Rangnekar, Prashant|work=The Indian Express|date=1 September 2009|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> Kapoor found filming for both of his characters at nearly the same time very difficult; he would shoot them on alternate days.<ref name="hard work">{{cite web|title=I worked hard for my shirtless scene in Kaminey: Shahid|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/i-worked-hard-for-my-shirtless-scene-in-kaminey-shahid/500236/|work=The Indian Express|date=10 August 2009|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref>

==Themes and influences==
According to the ''[[Hindustan Times]]'', ''Kaminey'' "is the first attempt to deal with reality in a mature, matter of fact manner."<ref name="ht" /> Unlike other Hindi films, in which the female lead is [[Sita]], the protagonist is [[Rama]] and the antagonist is [[Ravana]], the characters in ''Kaminey'' are nuanced humans in "layered and complex" situations.<ref name="ht">{{cite web|title=Review: Kaminey|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Kaminey/Article1-445201.aspx|author=Chaturvedi, Keshav|work=Hindustan Times|date=20 August 2009|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref> Namrata Joshi from ''[[Outlook (magazine)|Outlook]]'' wrote that ''Kaminey'' reflects Bhardwaj's "enduring fascination for underdogs, characters on the margins of society and the morally compromised".<ref name="outlook"/> Bhardwaj told Rediff.com that the film deals with "themes that affect our lives directly", and "is a reminder that we all have a dark side, and often we are not fully aware of that side".<ref name="rediff"/> Rakesh Bedi from ''[[The Economic Times]]'' wrote, "Bhardwaj presents the two warring brothers with speech defects. In today's world of logorrhea, communication is fraught with many dangers: misunderstandings, paranoias, recriminations, conflicts. Everyone speaks but no one understands. Bhardwaj gave the twins verbal impediments to show that the world has now been so hardwired to convoluted and calamitous communication that it needs silence or a speech defect to hash things out."<ref name="et">{{cite web|title=Kaminey picks all possible cinematic cliches|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/features/culture-cauldron/kaminey-picks-all-possible-cinematic-cliches/articleshow/4947045.cms|author=Bedi, Rakesh|work=The Economic Times|date=29 August 2009|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref> He continued, "[w]ith some glitches, Bhardwaj has almost re-birthed the Hindi film".<ref name="et"/> The film also explores sex and sexuality, which according to Bedi were explored in a "radically different and refreshing" way, and the director "daringly takes it a step further". When Sweety becomes pregnant, the couple "decide to carry the pregnancy to term after a bit of hesitation. So she literally pushes her man into marriage. (Had Bhardwaj abjured marriage, it would have been a complete break but the nuptials were essential to the drama of the film.)"<ref name="et"/> [[The Daily Beast]] said that "for aficionados of the Hindi-language genre, Kaminey is a revolutionary manifesto. It takes classic Bollywood tropes<U+2014>estranged brothers, a case of mistaken identity, high drama approaching slapstick comedy<U+2014>and presents them with Hollywood-style realism instead of Bollywood's wink-nudge mix of melodrama and posturing.<ref name="real">{{cite web|title=Bollywood Gets Real|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2009/11/26/bollywood-gets-real.html|publisher=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=26 November 2008|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref><ref name="rs">{{cite web|title=Kaminey review: Very very fexy|url=http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/aug/12/kaminey-review.htm|author=Sen, Raja|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|date=12 August 2009|accessdate=22 August 2009}}</ref>

Bhardwaj has been influenced by many directors{{mdash}}including [[Manmohan Desai]], [[Subhash Ghai]], [[Quentin Tarantino]] and [[Francis Ford Coppola]]{{mdash}}and combines these influences in his work.<ref>{{cite web|title=Uma Thurman is my heartthrob: Vishal|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-10-10/news-interviews/28076646_1_short-film-krzysztof-kieslowski-music|author=Dubey, Bharati|work=The Times of India|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref> Rakesh Bedi wrote that "Bhardwaj keeps displaying his vision throughout the film".<ref name="et"/> Reviewers have compared the film's multi-plot narrative to those of several films by Tarantino, [[Guy Ritchie]] and the [[Coen Brothers]]..<ref name="cnn">{{cite web|title=Masand's movie review: Kaminey|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masands-movie-review-kaminey-is-imaginative/99242-8-p0.html |author=Masand, Rajeev|publisher=[[CNN-IBN]]|date=15 August 2009|accessdate=22 August 2009}}</ref> Reviewers said that the film mostly belongs to the level of ''Pulp Fiction''; Shubhra Gupta of ''The Indian Express'' called it "Bollywood's first all-the-way-out-to-there pulp fiction".<ref name="tie">{{cite web|title=Movie Review: Kaminey|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/movie-review-kaminey/502164/0|author=Gupta, Shubhra|work=[[The Indian Express]]|date=14 August 2009|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> Bedi wrote, "there's [[Luis Bu<U+00F1>uel|Bu<U+00F1>uel]] in the Bengali dons, there's [[Akira Kurosawa|Kurosawa]]&nbsp;...&nbsp;in that surreal train car in which Charlie lives, there's [[Satyajit Ray|Ray]] in money-floating dreams that Charlie has".<ref name="et"/> Keshav Chaturvedi of the ''Hindustan Times'' compared the apocalyptical gang war in the climax to ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' (1979). He said, "Bhardwaj just demolishes the cliches of Bollywood. In ripping apart the stereotype, he gives us a prototype: a Bollywood that deals with alienation,&nbsp;...&nbsp;angst,&nbsp;...&nbsp; and atrocity."<ref name="ht"/> A review in ''The Times of India'' said that the film's climax reaches the level of ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]'', and described it as "absolutely riveting stuff, with the camera going on a hitherto unexplored journey in Indian cinema."<ref name="toir">{{cite news|title=Kaminey Review|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-08-14/bangalore/28200631_1_kaminey-charlie-priyanka-chopra|author=Kazmi, Nikhat|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=14 August 2009|accessdate = 22 August 2009}}</ref>

==Soundtrack==
{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->
